<body>
    <h1>Data Structures and Algorithms</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Internal data representation;</p></li>
<li>
<p>Abstract data types;</p></li>
<li>
<p>Elementary data structures: arrays, lists, stacks, queues, trees, graphs=
; </p></li>
<li>
<p>Advanced data Structures: heaps, Fibonacci heaps, B-trees;</p></li>
<li>
<p>Recursion, sorting, searching, hashing, storage management. Techniques f=
or analysis of algorithms; </p></li>
<li>
<p>Methods for the design of efficient algorithms: divide and conquer, gree=
dy method, dynamic programming, back tracking, branch and bound; <code><=
/code></p></li>
<li>
<p>Basic search and traversal techniques;</p></li>
<li>
<p>Topological sorting;</p></li>
<li>
<p>Connected components, spanning trees, shortest paths; </=
p></li>
<li>
<p>Flow algorithms;</p></li>
<li>
<p>Approximation algorithms;</p></li>
<li>
<p>Parallel algorithms;</p></li>
<li>
<p>Algebraic simplification and transformations;</p></li>
<li>
<p>Lower bound theory;</p></li>
<li>
<p>NP-completeness, NP-hard and NP- complete problems. </p>=
</li>
</ol>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Internal data representation;</p></li>
</ol>
<p></p>
<ol start=3D"2">
<li>
<p>Perfect =F0=9F=91=8F =E2=80=94 now let=E2=80=99s cover <strong>Internal =
Data Representation</strong>, a key topic in <strong>computer organization =
and digital systems</strong>. I=E2=80=99ll explain step by step.</p></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-=F0=9F=A7=A91.WhatisInternalDataRepre=
sentation?">=F0=9F=A7=A9 <strong>1. What is Internal Data Representation?</=
strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Internal data representation</strong> refers to <strong>how comp=
uters store and manipulate data</strong> internally.</p></li>
<li>
<p>All data (numbers, characters, instructions) must be <strong>represented=
 in binary</strong> for the digital system.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Main idea:</strong> Computers understand only <strong>0s and 1s<=
/strong>, so everything is stored in <strong>binary form</strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-=F0=9F=A7=A92.NumberRepresentation">=
=F0=9F=A7=A9 <strong>2. Number Representation</strong></h2>
<h3 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-a)BinaryNumberSystem"><strong>a) Bina=
ry Number System</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Base-2 system: digits are <strong>0 or 1</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p>Example: <code>1011=E2=82=82 =3D 1=C3=972=C2=B3 + 0=C3=972=C2=B2 + 1=C3=
=972=C2=B9 + 1=C3=972=E2=81=B0 =3D 11=E2=82=81=E2=82=80</code></p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-b)SignedNumbers"><strong>b) Signed Nu=
mbers</strong></h3>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Sign-Magnitude Representation</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>First bit =3D sign (0 for +, 1 for =E2=88=92)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Rest =3D magnitude</p></li>
<li>
<p>Example: +5 =E2=86=92 <code>0101</code>, =E2=88=925 =E2=86=92 <code>1101=
</code></p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>One=E2=80=99s Complement</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Negative number =3D <strong>invert all bits of positive number</strong><=
/p></li>
<li>
<p>Example: +5 =E2=86=92 <code>0101</code>, =E2=88=925 =E2=86=92 <code>1010=
</code></p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Two=E2=80=99s Complement</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Negative number =3D <strong>invert bits + 1</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p>Example: +5 =E2=86=92 <code>0101</code>, =E2=88=925 =E2=86=92 <code>1011=
</code></p></li>
<li>
<p>Most commonly used in computers</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-c)FractionalNumbers(FloatingPoint)"><=
strong>c) Fractional Numbers (Floating Point)</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Represent <strong>real numbers</strong> using <strong>mantissa and expon=
ent</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p>Standard: <strong>IEEE 754 format</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Single precision:</strong> 32 bits</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Double precision:</strong> 64 bits</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-d)OtherRepresentations"><strong>d) Ot=
her Representations</strong></h3>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>BCD (Binary-Coded Decimal)</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Each decimal digit stored as <strong>4-bit binary</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p>Example: 59 =E2=86=92 <code>0101 1001</code></p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>ASCII / Unicode</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Characters encoded in binary</p></li>
<li>
<p>ASCII =E2=86=92 7/8 bits, Unicode =E2=86=92 16 or 32 bits</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Packed / Unpacked Data</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Packed: multiple digits in one word</p></li>
<li>
<p>Unpacked: each digit occupies one word</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-=F0=9F=A7=A93.WhyInternalRepresentati=
onMatters">=F0=9F=A7=A9 <strong>3. Why Internal Representation Matters</str=
ong></h2>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Determines <strong>range of numbers</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p>Affects <strong>arithmetic operations</strong> (add, subtract, multiply)=
</p></li>
<li>
<p>Affects <strong>memory usage</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p>Crucial for <strong>efficient computing and data transfer</strong></p></=
li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-=F0=9F=94=B94.QuickSummaryTable">=F0=
=9F=94=B9 <strong>4. Quick Summary Table</strong></h2>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"fc=
62560c-3a5d-4f3a-951d-50867e404400" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Data Type</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Representation</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Notes</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Integer</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Binary, Sign-Magnitude, One=E2=80=99s Complement, Two=E2=80=99s Compleme=
nt</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Two=E2=80=99s complement widely used</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Real Numbers</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Floating Point (IEEE 754)</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Mantissa + Exponent</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Decimal</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>BCD</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Each decimal digit =E2=86=92 4 bits</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Characters</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>ASCII, Unicode</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Encode letters, symbols, etc.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Packed Data</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Multiple digits in one word</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Saves memory</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Unpacked Data</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Each digit in separate word</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Simple but uses more memory</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<p>=E2=9C=85 <strong>In Short:</strong></p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Internal data representation</strong> is how computers <strong>s=
tore and manipulate numbers, characters, and instructions</strong> in <stro=
ng>binary form</strong>.<br>
Understanding this is crucial for <strong>arithmetic operations, memory man=
agement, and efficient program execution</strong>.Abstract data types;</p>
</blockquote>
<p></p>
<ol start=3D"3">
<li>
<p>Elementary data structures: arrays, lists, stacks, queues, trees, graphs=
; </p></li>
</ol>
<p>Perfect =F0=9F=91=8F =E2=80=94 now let=E2=80=99s cover <strong>Elementar=
y Data Structures</strong>, a core topic in <strong>computer science and pr=
ogramming</strong>. I=E2=80=99ll explain clearly and step by step.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-=F0=9F=A7=A91.WhatareDataStructures?"=
>=F0=9F=A7=A9 <strong>1. What are Data Structures?</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Data structures</strong> are <strong>ways of organizing and stor=
ing data</strong> in memory so that it can be <strong>used efficiently</str=
ong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>They provide <strong>efficient access, insertion, deletion, and traversa=
l</strong> of data.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-=F0=9F=A7=A92.Arrays">=F0=9F=A7=A9 <s=
trong>2. Arrays</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> Collection of <strong>elements of the same =
type</strong>, stored <strong>contiguously</strong> in memory.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Access:</strong> Using <strong>index</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Operations:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Access: <code>arr[i]</code> =E2=86=92 O(1)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Insertion/Deletion: O(n)</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Example:</strong> <code>int arr[5] =3D {1,2,3,4,5}</code></p></l=
i>
</ul>
<p><strong>Pros:</strong> Fast access by index<br><strong>Cons:</strong> Fi=
xed size, costly insertion/deletion</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-=F0=9F=A7=A93.Lists">=F0=9F=A7=A9 <st=
rong>3. Lists</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> Collection of elements connected by <strong=
>links/pointers</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Types:</strong></p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Singly Linked List</strong> =E2=80=93 Each node points to next n=
ode</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Doubly Linked List</strong> =E2=80=93 Each node points to next a=
nd previous</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Circular Linked List</strong> =E2=80=93 Last node points back to=
 first</p></li>
</ol></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Operations:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Traversal: O(n)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Insertion/Deletion: O(1) if position known</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Pros:</strong> Dynamic size, easy insertion/deletion<br><strong>=
Cons:</strong> Slower access by index</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-=F0=9F=A7=A94.Stack">=F0=9F=A7=A9 <st=
rong>4. Stack</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> Linear structure following <strong>LIFO (La=
st In, First Out)</strong> principle.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Operations:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><code>push(x)</code> =E2=86=92 insert at top</p></li>
<li>
<p><code>pop()</code> =E2=86=92 remove top</p></li>
<li>
<p><code>peek()</code> =E2=86=92 view top without removing</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Applications:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Expression evaluation (infix =E2=86=92 postfix)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Undo/Redo operations</p></li>
<li>
<p>Function call management (recursion)</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-=F0=9F=A7=A95.Queue">=F0=9F=A7=A9 <st=
rong>5. Queue</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> Linear structure following <strong>FIFO (Fi=
rst In, First Out)</strong> principle.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Types:</strong></p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Simple Queue</strong> =E2=80=93 Enqueue at rear, dequeue at fron=
t</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Circular Queue</strong> =E2=80=93 Efficient memory use</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Priority Queue</strong> =E2=80=93 Element with highest priority =
dequeued first</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Deque</strong> =E2=80=93 Double-ended queue</p></li>
</ol></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Applications:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>CPU scheduling</p></li>
<li>
<p>Printer queue</p></li>
<li>
<p>Network packet management</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-=F0=9F=A7=A96.Trees">=F0=9F=A7=A9 <st=
rong>6. Trees</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> Hierarchical structure with <strong>nodes</=
strong> connected by <strong>edges</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Components:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Root:</strong> Top node</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Parent/Child nodes</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Leaves:</strong> Nodes with no children</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Types:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Binary Tree, Binary Search Tree (BST), AVL Tree, Heap, etc.</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Applications:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Hierarchical data representation</p></li>
<li>
<p>Searching and sorting (BST)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Expression parsing (expression tree)</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-=F0=9F=A7=A97.Graphs">=F0=9F=A7=A9 <s=
trong>7. Graphs</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> Set of <strong>vertices (nodes)</strong> co=
nnected by <strong>edges</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Types:</strong></p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Directed / Undirected</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Weighted / Unweighted</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Cyclic / Acyclic</strong></p></li>
</ol></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Representation:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Adjacency Matrix</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Adjacency List</strong></p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Applications:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Social networks</p></li>
<li>
<p>Routing algorithms (shortest path)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Dependency resolution</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-=F0=9F=94=B98.QuickSummaryTable">=F0=
=9F=94=B9 <strong>8. Quick Summary Table</strong></h2>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"be=
0b3702-56a3-4455-a584-43f810f62ebb" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Data Structure</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Organization</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Access</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Key Operations</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Applications</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Array</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Contiguous</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Index</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
