<p>=E2=9C=85 <strong>In Short:</strong></p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Recursion</strong> simplifies divide-and-conquer problems.<br><s=
trong>Sorting and searching</strong> organize and find data efficiently.<br=
><strong>Hashing</strong> provides near-constant time access.<br><strong>St=
orage management</strong> optimizes memory use.<br><strong>Algorithm analys=
is</strong> predicts efficiency and helps choose optimal solutions.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol start=3D"6">
<li>
<p>Methods for the design of efficient algorithms: divide and conquer, gree=
dy method, dynamic programming, back tracking, branch and bound; <code><=
/code></p></li>
</ol>
<p>Perfect =F0=9F=91=8F =E2=80=94 now let=E2=80=99s cover <strong>Methods f=
or Designing Efficient Algorithms</strong>, a core topic in <strong>algorit=
hm design</strong>. I=E2=80=99ll explain step by step.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-=F0=9F=A7=A91.DivideandConquer">=F0=
=9F=A7=A9 <strong>1. Divide and Conquer</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> Break a problem into <strong>smaller subpro=
blems</strong>, solve them <strong>recursively</strong>, and <strong>combin=
e their solutions</strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-Steps:"><strong>Steps:</strong></h3>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Divide the problem into subproblems</p></li>
<li>
<p>Conquer each subproblem recursively</p></li>
<li>
<p>Combine results to form the solution</p></li>
</ol>
<h3 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-Examples:.1"><strong>Examples:</stron=
g></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Merge Sort</p></li>
<li>
<p>Quick Sort</p></li>
<li>
<p>Binary Search</p></li>
<li>
<p>Strassen=E2=80=99s Matrix Multiplication</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-Advantages:.1"><strong>Advantages:</s=
trong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Reduces problem size</p></li>
<li>
<p>Often leads to <strong>logarithmic or linearithmic complexity</strong></=
p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-=F0=9F=A7=A92.GreedyMethod">=F0=9F=A7=
=A9 <strong>2. Greedy Method</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> Build a solution <strong>step by step</stro=
ng>, always choosing the <strong>best option at the current step</strong> (=
local optimum).</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-Characteristics:"><strong>Characteris=
tics:</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Works well when <strong>local optimum =3D global optimum</strong></p></l=
i>
<li>
<p>Simple and fast</p></li>
<li>
<p>Not guaranteed to work for all problems</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-Examples:.2"><strong>Examples:</stron=
g></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Minimum Spanning Tree (Prim=E2=80=99s, Kruskal=E2=80=99s algorithms)</p>=
</li>
<li>
<p>Dijkstra=E2=80=99s Shortest Path Algorithm</p></li>
<li>
<p>Fractional Knapsack Problem</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-=F0=9F=A7=A93.DynamicProgramming(DP)"=
>=F0=9F=A7=A9 <strong>3. Dynamic Programming (DP)</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> Solve <strong>complex problems by breaking =
them into overlapping subproblems</strong> and <strong>storing results</str=
ong> to avoid recomputation.</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-Steps:.1"><strong>Steps:</strong></h3=
>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Identify <strong>subproblems</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p>Solve each subproblem <strong>once</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p>Store results in <strong>table (memoization or tabulation)</strong></p><=
/li>
<li>
<p>Use stored results to solve bigger problem</p></li>
</ol>
<h3 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-Examples:.3"><strong>Examples:</stron=
g></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Fibonacci series (optimized)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Longest Common Subsequence (LCS)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Knapsack Problem (0/1)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Matrix Chain Multiplication</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-Advantages:.2"><strong>Advantages:</s=
trong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Optimizes <strong>recursive solutions</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p>Reduces <strong>time complexity</strong> significantly</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-=F0=9F=A7=A94.Backtracking">=F0=9F=A7=
=A9 <strong>4. Backtracking</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> Solve problems by <strong>exploring all pos=
sible solutions</strong> and <strong>discarding infeasible solutions</stron=
g> early.</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-Characteristics:.1"><strong>Character=
istics:</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Explore all <strong>candidate solutions</strong> recursively</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Prune</strong> paths that cannot lead to a solution</p></li>
<li>
<p>Often used for <strong>constraint satisfaction problems</strong></p></li=
>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-Examples:.4"><strong>Examples:</stron=
g></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>N-Queens Problem</p></li>
<li>
<p>Sudoku Solver</p></li>
<li>
<p>Graph Coloring</p></li>
<li>
<p>Hamiltonian Path Problem</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-=F0=9F=A7=A95.BranchandBound">=F0=9F=
=A7=A9 <strong>5. Branch and Bound</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> Systematically explore <strong>solution spa=
ce</strong> using a <strong>state-space tree</strong>, and <strong>discard =
branches</strong> that cannot yield better solution than current best.</p><=
/li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-Characteristics:.2"><strong>Character=
istics:</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Uses <strong>upper and lower bounds</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p>Prunes <strong>unpromising branches</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p>Often used for <strong>optimization problems</strong></p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-Examples:.5"><strong>Examples:</stron=
g></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Traveling Salesman Problem (TSP)</p></li>
<li>
<p>0/1 Knapsack Problem</p></li>
<li>
<p>Job Scheduling Problem</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-=F0=9F=94=B96.ComparisonTable">=F0=9F=
=94=B9 <strong>6. Comparison Table</strong></h2>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"f1=
0c6d71-dab5-4581-b88e-4cc032833e6e" class=3D"confluenceTable">
