<p>=E2=9C=85 <strong>In Short:</strong></p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Search techniques</strong> locate elements (linear, binary, hash=
).<br><strong>Traversal techniques</strong> systematically visit all elemen=
ts or nodes (DFS, BFS).<br>
Choosing the right method <strong>depends on data structure and application=
</strong>.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol start=3D"8">
<li>
<p>Topological sorting;</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Perfect =F0=9F=91=8F =E2=80=94 now let=E2=80=99s cover <strong>Topologic=
al Sorting</strong>, an important topic in <strong>graph algorithms</strong=
>. I=E2=80=99ll explain step by step.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-=F0=9F=A7=A91.WhatisTopologicalSortin=
g?">=F0=9F=A7=A9 <strong>1. What is Topological Sorting?</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> A <strong>linear ordering of vertices</stro=
ng> in a <strong>directed acyclic graph (DAG)</strong> such that for every =
directed edge <strong>u =E2=86=92 v</strong>, vertex <strong>u</strong> com=
es <strong>before v</strong> in the ordering.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Represents <strong>dependencies between tasks<=
/strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-=F0=9F=A7=A92.KeyPoints">=F0=9F=A7=A9=
 <strong>2. Key Points</strong></h2>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Works <strong>only for DAGs</strong> (no cycles allowed)</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Multiple valid topological orders</strong> may exist</p></li>
<li>
<p>Useful in <strong>scheduling, task ordering, and build systems</strong><=
/p></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-=F0=9F=A7=A93.Applications">=F0=9F=A7=
=A9 <strong>3. Applications</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Task scheduling with dependencies</p></li>
<li>
<p>Course prerequisite ordering</p></li>
<li>
<p>Build systems (compilation order)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Data serialization</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-=F0=9F=A7=A94.AlgorithmsforTopologica=
lSorting">=F0=9F=A7=A9 <strong>4. Algorithms for Topological Sorting</stron=
g></h2>
<h3 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-a)Kahn=E2=80=99sAlgorithm(BFS-Based)"=
><strong>a) Kahn=E2=80=99s Algorithm (BFS-Based)</strong></h3>
<p><strong>Steps:</strong></p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Compute <strong>in-degree</strong> (number of incoming edges) for each v=
ertex</p></li>
<li>
<p>Initialize a <strong>queue</strong> with vertices having <strong>in-degr=
ee =3D 0</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p>While queue not empty:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Remove vertex <code>u</code> from queue</p></li>
<li>
<p>Add <code>u</code> to topological order</p></li>
<li>
<p>Decrease in-degree of all neighbors of <code>u</code></p></li>
<li>
<p>If in-degree of a neighbor becomes 0 =E2=86=92 enqueue it</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Time Complexity:</strong> O(V + E)<br><strong>Space Complexity:<=
/strong> O(V)</p>
<hr>
<h3 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-b)DFS-BasedAlgorithm"><strong>b) DFS-=
Based Algorithm</strong></h3>
<p><strong>Steps:</strong></p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Perform <strong>DFS traversal</strong> of the graph</p></li>
<li>
<p>After visiting all neighbors of a vertex <code>v</code>, <strong>push </=
strong><code>v</code><strong> onto a stack</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p>Once DFS completes for all vertices, <strong>pop vertices from the stack=
</strong> =E2=86=92 gives topological order</p></li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Time Complexity:</strong> O(V + E)<br><strong>Space Complexity:<=
/strong> O(V)</p>
<hr>
