<p><strong>Topological sorting</strong> produces a <strong>linear ordering =
of DAG vertices</strong> respecting dependencies.<br>
It is widely used in <strong>scheduling, compilation, and task management</=
strong>, and can be implemented using <strong>Kahn=E2=80=99s algorithm (BFS=
)</strong> or <strong>DFS with a stack</strong>.</p>
</blockquote>
<ol start=3D"9">
<li>
<p>Connected components, spanning trees, shortest paths; </=
p></li>
</ol>
<p>Perfect =F0=9F=91=8F =E2=80=94 now let=E2=80=99s cover <strong>Connected=
 Components, Spanning Trees, and Shortest Paths</strong>, which are fundame=
ntal in <strong>graph theory and algorithms</strong>. I=E2=80=99ll explain =
step by step.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-=F0=9F=A7=A91.ConnectedComponents">=
=F0=9F=A7=A9 <strong>1. Connected Components</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> A <strong>connected component</strong> of a=
 graph is a <strong>maximal set of vertices</strong> such that there exists=
 a <strong>path between every pair of vertices</strong> in the set.</p></li=
>
<li>
<p><strong>Types of Graphs:</strong></p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Undirected Graphs:</strong> A connected component is a set of ve=
rtices where every vertex is reachable from every other vertex in the set.<=
/p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Directed Graphs:</strong> Strongly connected components (SCC) ar=
e subsets of vertices where <strong>every vertex is reachable from every ot=
her vertex</strong> in the subset.</p></li>
</ol></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-AlgorithmstoFindConnectedComponents">=
<strong>Algorithms to Find Connected Components</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>DFS / BFS:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Start DFS/BFS from an unvisited vertex</p></li>
<li>
<p>All reachable vertices form a connected component</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Kosaraju=E2=80=99s / Tarjan=E2=80=99s Algorithm:</strong> For <s=
trong>strongly connected components in directed graphs</strong></p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-Applications.4"><strong>Applications<=
/strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Social networks (groups of friends)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Image processing (connected regions)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Network connectivity analysis</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-=F0=9F=A7=A92.SpanningTrees">=F0=9F=
=A7=A9 <strong>2. Spanning Trees</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> A <strong>spanning tree</strong> of a conne=
cted graph is a <strong>subgraph that includes all vertices</strong>, is <s=
trong>connected</strong>, and has <strong>no cycles</strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-Types"><strong>Types</strong></h3>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Minimum Spanning Tree (MST):</strong> Spanning tree with <strong=
>minimum total edge weight</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Algorithms to Find MST:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Kruskal=E2=80=99s Algorithm</strong>: Sort edges by weight, add =
edges avoiding cycles</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Prim=E2=80=99s Algorithm</strong>: Start from a vertex, add the =
<strong>minimum weight edge</strong> connecting tree to remaining vertices<=
/p></li>
</ul></li>
</ol>
<h3 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-Properties"><strong>Properties</stron=
g></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>A graph with <strong>V vertices</strong> =E2=86=92 spanning tree has <st=
rong>V-1 edges</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p>Useful in <strong>network design, routing, and clustering</strong></p></=
li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-=F0=9F=A7=A93.ShortestPaths">=F0=9F=
=A7=A9 <strong>3. Shortest Paths</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> Find the <strong>minimum-cost path</strong>=
 between two vertices in a graph.</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-Algorithms"><strong>Algorithms</stron=
g></h3>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Dijkstra=E2=80=99s Algorithm</strong> (for non-negative weights)=
</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Uses a <strong>priority queue</strong> to pick vertex with minimum dista=
nce</p></li>
<li>
<p>Time Complexity: O(V + E log V) using min-heap</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Bellman-Ford Algorithm</strong> (for negative weights)</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Can handle <strong>negative edge weights</strong>, detects negative cycl=
es</p></li>
<li>
<p>Time Complexity: O(V =C3=97 E)</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Floyd-Warshall Algorithm</strong> (All-pairs shortest path)</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Dynamic programming approach</p></li>
<li>
<p>Time Complexity: O(V=C2=B3)</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ol>
<h3 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-Applications.5"><strong>Applications<=
/strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p>GPS navigation</p></li>
<li>
<p>Network routing (Internet packet routing)</p></li>
<li>
<p>Traffic and logistics optimization</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
