<p>Algebraic simplification and transformations;</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Perfect =F0=9F=91=8F =E2=80=94 now let=E2=80=99s cover <strong>Algebraic=
 Simplification and Transformations</strong>, a fundamental topic in <stron=
g>digital logic and Boolean algebra</strong>. I=E2=80=99ll explain step by =
step.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-=F0=9F=A7=A91.WhatisAlgebraicSimplifi=
cation?">=F0=9F=A7=A9 <strong>1. What is Algebraic Simplification?</strong>=
</h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Definition:</strong> The process of <strong>reducing a Boolean e=
xpression</strong> to its <strong>simplest or minimal form</strong> using <=
strong>Boolean algebra rules</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Goal:</strong> Reduce the number of <strong>gates, inputs, and c=
omplexity</strong> in digital circuits.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-=F0=9F=A7=A92.BasicBooleanAlgebraLaws=
">=F0=9F=A7=A9 <strong>2. Basic Boolean Algebra Laws</strong></h2>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Identity Law:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>( A + 0 =3D A )</p></li>
<li>
<p>( A \cdot 1 =3D A )</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Null Law:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>( A + 1 =3D 1 )</p></li>
<li>
<p>( A \cdot 0 =3D 0 )</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Idempotent Law:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>( A + A =3D A )</p></li>
<li>
<p>( A \cdot A =3D A )</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Complement Law:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>( A + A' =3D 1 )</p></li>
<li>
<p>( A \cdot A' =3D 0 )</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Commutative Law:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>( A + B =3D B + A )</p></li>
<li>
<p>( A \cdot B =3D B \cdot A )</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Associative Law:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>( (A + B) + C =3D A + (B + C) )</p></li>
<li>
<p>( (A \cdot B) \cdot C =3D A \cdot (B \cdot C) )</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Distributive Law:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>( A \cdot (B + C) =3D A \cdot B + A \cdot C )</p></li>
<li>
<p>( A + (B \cdot C) =3D (A + B) \cdot (A + C) )</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-=F0=9F=A7=A93.BooleanTransformations"=
>=F0=9F=A7=A9 <strong>3. Boolean Transformations</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Purpose:</strong> Convert Boolean expressions into <strong>diffe=
rent equivalent forms</strong> to simplify or implement circuits efficientl=
y.</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-CommonTransformations:"><strong>Commo=
n Transformations:</strong></h3>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>De Morgan=E2=80=99s Theorems</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>( (A \cdot B)' =3D A' + B' )</p></li>
<li>
<p>( (A + B)' =3D A' \cdot B' )</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Absorption Law:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>( A + A \cdot B =3D A )</p></li>
<li>
<p>( A \cdot (A + B) =3D A )</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Consensus Theorem:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>( AB + A'C + BC =3D AB + A'C )</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Double Negation:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>( (A')' =3D A )</p></li>
</ul></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-=F0=9F=A7=A94.StepsinAlgebraicSimplif=
ication">=F0=9F=A7=A9 <strong>4. Steps in Algebraic Simplification</strong>=
</h2>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Identify terms that can be combined</strong> using basic laws</p=
></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Apply De Morgan=E2=80=99s Theorem</strong> if complemented expre=
ssions exist</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Use distributive, associative, and commutative laws</strong> to =
rearrange terms</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Eliminate redundant terms</strong> using absorption and idempote=
nt laws</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Check if further reduction</strong> is possible</p></li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-=F0=9F=A7=A95.Example.1">=F0=9F=A7=A9=
 <strong>5. Example</strong></h2>
<p>Simplify:<br>
[<br>
F =3D A \cdot B + A \cdot B'<br>
]</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong><br>
[<br>
F =3D A \cdot (B + B') \quad \text{(Distributive Law)}<br>
]<br>
[<br>
F =3D A \cdot 1 \quad \text{(Complement Law)}<br>
]<br>
[<br>
F =3D A \quad \text{(Identity Law)}<br>
]</p>
<p>=E2=9C=85 Result: <strong>F =3D A</strong></p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"DataStructuresandAlgorithms-=F0=9F=94=B96.QuickSummaryTable.3">=
=F0=9F=94=B9 <strong>6. Quick Summary Table</strong></h2>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"760" data-layout=3D"default" data-local-id=3D"52=
